23 (L) “INDIVIDUAL NONJOINT APPRENTICESHIP PROGRAM” HAS THE
24 MEANING STATED IN § 14–801 OF THIS ARTICLE.
25 [(g)] (M) (1) “Locality” means the county in which the work is to be performed.
26 (2) If the public work is located within 2 or more counties, the locality
27 includes all counties in which the public work is located.

6 HOUSE BILL 1165
1 [(h)] (N) “Mechanical systems service contract” means a contract for:
2 (1) HVAC systems, including heating, ventilation, ductwork, and
3 cooling/air–conditioning equipment;
4 (2) refrigeration systems;
5 (3) plumbing systems, including pipes, tanks, fittings, and other elements
6 that control the water and gas supply, heating, and sanitation of a building;
7 (4) electrical systems, including electrical components that supply,
8 distribute, generate, and use electrical power, overhead and underground lines, poles,
9 transformers, and other related equipment; and
10 (5) elevator systems, including escalators, moving walkways, and other
11 conveyances.
12 [(i)] (O) “Prevailing wage rate” means the hourly rate of wages paid in the
13 locality as determined by the Commissioner under § 17–208 of this subtitle.
14 [(j)] (P) (1) “Public body” means:
15 (i) the State;
16 (ii) except as provided in paragraph (2)(i) of this subsection, a unit of
17 the State government or instrumentality of the State;
18 (iii) any political subdivision, agency, person, or entity with respect
19 to the construction of any public work for which 25% or more of the money used for
20 construction is State money;
21 (iv) notwithstanding paragraph (2)(ii) of this subsection, a political
22 subdivision if its governing body:
23 1. provides by ordinance or resolution that the political
24 subdivision is covered by this subtitle; and
25 2. gives written notice of that ordinance or resolution to the
26 Commissioner; and
27 (v) the Washington Suburban Sanitary Commission.
28 (2) “Public body” does not include:

HOUSE BILL 1165 7
1 (i) except as provided in paragraph (1)(v) of this subsection, a unit
2 of the State government or instrumentality of the State funded wholly from a source other
3 than the State; or
4 (ii) any political subdivision, agency, person, or entity with respect
5 to the construction of any public work for which less than 25% of the money used for
6 construction is State money.
7 [(k)] (Q) (1) Subject to paragraph (2) of this subsection, “public work” means
8 a structure or work, including a bridge, building, ditch, road, alley, waterwork, or sewage
9 disposal plant, that:
10 (i) is constructed for public use or benefit; or
11 (ii) is paid for wholly or partly by public money.
12 (2) “Public work” does not include:
13 (i) unless let to contract, a structure or work whose construction is
14 performed by a public service company under order of the Public Service Commission or
15 other public authority regardless of:
16 1. public supervision or direction; or
17 2. payment wholly or partly from public money; or
18 (ii) a capital project that receives State funds in the annual State
19 capital budget as:
20 1. a local House of Delegates initiative; or
21 2. a local Senate initiative.
22 [(l)] (R) “Public work contract” means a contract for construction of a public
23 work.
24 (S) “WAIVER APPRENTICESHIP PROGRAM” HAS THE MEANING STATED IN §
25 14–801 OF THIS ARTICLE.
26 [(m)] (T) “Worker” means a laborer or mechanic.
27 17–205.
28 (a) A contractor or subcontractor under a public work contract subject to this
29 subtitle:

8 HOUSE BILL 1165
1 (1) shall employ only competent workers and apprentices who qualify
2 under subsection (b) of this section;
3 (2) may not employ any individual classified as a helper or trainee; and
4 (3) may refuse to employ a worker who is a resident of another state if the
5 Commissioner finds that the other state enforces a law that prohibits a resident of this
6 State from employment as a worker under a public work contract in that state, unless:
7 (i) the refusal is in conflict or otherwise inconsistent with a federal
8 law applicable to the public work;
9 (ii) the federal government is to pay wholly or partly for the public
10 work; and
11 (iii) the inconsistency with federal law jeopardizes the availability of
12 federal funds for the public work.
13 (b) An apprentice under a public work contract shall be part of and used in
14 accordance with an apprenticeship program THAT:
15 (1) IS registered with the Council and approved by the Office of
16 Apprenticeship of the United States Department of Labor; AND
17 (2) IF THE PROGRAM HAS GRADUATED AT LEAST ONE
18 APPRENTICESHIP COHORT, HAS A COMPLETION RATE OF AT LEAST 25%, AS
19 DETERMINED BY THE MARYLAND DEPARTMENT OF LABOR.
20 17–601.
21 (a) In this subtitle the following words have the meanings indicated.
22 (b) “Apprenticeship training program” means an apprenticeship training
23 program that:
24 (1) is registered with, and approved by, the Apprenticeship and Training
25 Council or the U.S. Department of Labor; AND
26 (2) HAS A COMPLETION RATE OF AT LEAST 25%, AS DETERMINED BY
27 THE DEPARTMENT.
28 (e) “Department” means the Maryland Department of Labor.
29 (f) “Fund” means the State Apprenticeship Training Fund established under §
30 17–602 of this subtitle.

HOUSE BILL 1165 9
1 (g) “Participates in an apprenticeship training program” means that a contractor
2 or subcontractor makes regular financial contributions for each covered craft to
3 apprenticeship training programs for covered crafts during the term of the covered project
4 that are at least equal to the hourly fringe benefit contribution rates required for
5 apprenticeship training by the applicable prevailing wage determination for the project, as
6 specified by the Secretary.
7 (h) “Secretary” means the Secretary of Labor.
